#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:3 001f4b11b2ce4ca3937044041a23bf31
msgid "Coding style"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:7 f66088ecbe58454a93fd77573d368840
msgid "Rationale"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:10 4e9e570676b84d53a7565d4b08174858
msgid ""
"Maintaining proper coding style is very important for any large software "
"project, such as Qubes. Here’s why:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:12 66b13eaed57040a89d75e93f03188756
msgid ""
"It eases maintenance tasks, such as adding new functionality or "
"generalizing code later,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:14 cf4ad3b2988e4f54bf71f1bbf75edb3c
msgid ""
"It allows others (as well as the future you!) to easily understand "
"fragments of code and what they were supposed to do, and thus makes it "
"easier to later extend them with newer functionality or bug fixes,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:16 aad69df80baa44ceba9ada26e17d39dd
msgid "It allows others to easily review the code and catch various bugs,"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:18 f84ffd3b6b2f48c38986fc44742e717b
msgid ""
"It provides for an aesthetically pleasing experience when one reads the "
"code…"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:22 31cf2c36cc4e4a9faec7bbc6b73e95b0
msgid ""
"Often, developers, usually smart ones, undersell the value of proper "
"coding style, thinking that it’s much more important how their code "
"works. These developers expect that if their code solves some problem "
"using a nice and neat trick, then that’s all that is really required. "
"Such thinking shows, however, immaturity and is a signal that the "
"developer, no matter how bright and smart, might not be a good fit for "
"larger projects. Writing a clever exploit for a Black Hat show is one "
"thing - writing useful software supposed to be used and maintained for "
"years is quite a different story. If you want to show off what a smart "
"programmer you are, then you should become a researcher and write "
"exploits. If, on the other hand, you want to be part of a team that makes"
" real, useful software, you should ensure your coding style is "
"impeccable. At Qubes project, we often took shortcuts and wrote nasty "
"code, and this has always back fired at us, sometime months, sometime "
"years later, the net result being we had to spend time fixing code, "
"rather than implementing new functionality."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:24 c2b2213c8fc24b4aa29c156c1e86cfa4
msgid ""
"And here’s a `link to the real case "
"<https://groups.google.com/forum/#!msg/qubes-"
"devel/XgTo6L8-5XA/JLOadvBqnqMJ>`__ (one Qubes Security Bulletin) "
"demonstrating how the lackadaisical coding style lead to a real security "
"bug. Never assume you’re smart enough to disregard clean and rigorous "
"coding!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:27 d2f891f570954b8f89341ddaa8f5791e
msgid "General typographic conventions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:30 3b18dd00592b4a4f9cee5a0d71f687e3
msgid ""
"**Use space-expanded tabs that equal 4 spaces.** Yes, we know, there are "
"many arguments for using “real” tabs instead of space-expanded tabs, but "
"we need to pick one convention to make the project consistent. One "
"argument for using space-expanded tabs is that this way the programmer is"
" in control of how the code will look like, despite how other users have "
"configured their editors to visualize the tabs (of course, we assume any "
"sane person uses a fixed-width font for viewing the source code). If it "
"makes you feel any better, assume this is just an arbitrary choice made "
"to enforce a unified style."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:32 05ccf1af432140efb721c0eac674fc21
msgid ""
"**Maintain max. line length of 80 characters**. Even though today’s "
"monitors often are very wide and it’s often not a problem to have 120 "
"characters displayed in an editor, maintaining shorter line lengths "
"improves readability. It also allows others to have two parallel windows "
"open, side by side, each with different parts of the source code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:34 bb50f9d0b47f4ab787622fa67a0f025e
msgid "**Naming conventions for any OS other than Windows**:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:36 86722d68cf484684a1d8f5516214bb75
msgid "``ClassName``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:38 f700bfe8b654486a997626f659bf5807
msgid "``some_variable``, ``some_function``, ``some_argument``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:42 5b05dd452ed2400b8baaa9a13b3f5c97
msgid ""
"**Naming convention for Windows OS** – exceptionally to preserve Windows "
"conventions please use the following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:44 6b85b09953f847ec829f687590d9fa9d
msgid "``ClassName``, ``FunctionName``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:46 00794340600047a687ab454ab60061a1
msgid ""
"``pszArgumentOne``, ``hPipe`` – use Hungarian notation for argument and "
"variables"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:50 5e24c020d90b43f382796e488765405e
msgid ""
"**Maintain a decent amount of horizontal spacing**, e.g. add a space "
"after ``if`` or before ``{`` in C, and similar in other languages. "
"Whether and where to also use spaces within expressions, such as (x*2+5) "
"vs. (x * 2 + 5) is left to the developer’s judgment. Do not put spaces "
"immediately after or before the brackets in expressions, so avoid "
"constructs like this: ``if ( condition )`` and use ones like this: ``if "
"(condition)`` instead."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:52 4423bd8ce3e44299ad23b038c36e7ff3
msgid ""
"**Use single new lines** (‘\\\\n’ aka LF) in any non-Windows source code."
" On Windows, exceptionally, use the CRLF line endings (–). This will "
"allow the source code to be easily viewable in various Windows-based "
"programs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:54 3e5ab969650047e9810d9d47a7b8fe3c
msgid ""
"**Use descriptive names for variables and functions**! Really, at a time "
"when most editors have auto-completion features, there is no excuse for "
"using short variable names."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:56 6879ee2be5b94fbbb6650d2b20f4a09c
msgid "**Comments should be indented together with the code**, e.g. like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:72 e5cc81bc49a746dfb136c23a1e736049
msgid "File naming conventions"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:75 4a97bdc93c5340c39445d59c07eb91e4
msgid ""
"All file names written with small letters, use dash to separate words, "
"rather than underscores, e.g. ``qubes-dom0-update``. Never use spaces!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:79 2a7d221d68d6454fa5dc779a09c3c321
msgid "**File naming in Linux/Unix-like systems:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:81 c0298f18bce3432e9083803dfcc317e2
msgid ""
"User commands that operate on particular VMs (also those accessible in "
"VMs): ``/usr/bin/qvm-*``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:83 c9e5d73a2ae34e72bc86b97b60b147ed
msgid ""
"User commands that apply to the whole system (Dom0 only): "
"``/usr/bin/qubes-*``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:85 804fba1b72fe436dbe652ad0edc8e247
msgid ""
"Auxiliary executables and scripts in ``/usr/libexec/qubes/`` (**Note:** "
"previously we used ``/usr/lib/qubes`` but decided to change that)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:87 d0bab64c490148d78208d2aa2f603d2f
msgid "Helper, non-executable files in ``/usr/share/qubes/``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:89 358d3a8a65864dcbbffb13212c0b55af
msgid "Various config files in ``/etc/qubes``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:91 2fe8e2db98124ab2b8d5c84a9f9910bb
msgid ""
"Qubes RPC services in ``/etc/qubes-rpc``. Qubes RPC Policy definitions "
"(only in Dom0) in ``/etc/qubes-rpc/policy/``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:93 b6169676cccd4c5a8a4a84f1139e9083
msgid "All VM-related configs, images, and other files in ``/var/lib/qubes/``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:95 0b9982c485ec4cee8512e5be1a38d80a
msgid ""
"System-wide temporary files which reflect the current state of system in "
"``/var/run/qubes``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:97 ce2cac66806c4af1bc501ea591869dff
msgid "Logs: either log to the system-wide messages, or to ``/var/log/qubes/``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:101 3c2b17f460d64e43baab313cd65badb0
msgid "**File naming in Windows systems:**"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:103 fb644d2b0d8c40b29e94bba0223e0b31
msgid ""
"All base qubes-related files in ``C:\\Program Files\\Invisible Things "
"Lab\\Qubes\\`` (Exceptionally spaces are allowed here to adhere to "
"Windows naming conventions)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:105 a0a699da243048388a5ab25515bb9820
msgid ""
"Other, third-party files, not Qubes-specific, such as e.g. Xen PV drivers"
" might be in different vendor subdirs, e.g. ``C:\\Program Files\\Xen PV "
"Drivers``"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:110 84ae9cab74e94945abac5e4d7a1b204f
msgid "General programming style guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:113 b4377213a040409d85a70be5452eade9
msgid ""
"Do not try to impress with your coding kung-fu, do not use tricks to save"
" 2 lines of code, always prefer readability over trickiness!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:115 d38ff15864d8452aaebc2e8516098146
msgid "Make sure your code compiles and builds without warnings."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:117 2b635407ebb949afa700014f1859ba60
msgid ""
"Always think first about interfaces (e.g. function arguments, or class "
"methods) and data structures before you start writing the actual code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:119 16ab86a3f86c418fbba4920abed7a532
msgid ""
"Use comments to explain non-trivial code fragments, or expected behavior "
"of more complex functions, if it is not clear from their name."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:121 f59a7e7ed68f42679e8506db46ca80b8
msgid ""
"Do **not** use comments for code fragments where it is immediately clear "
"what the code does. E.g. avoid constructs like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:133 73274f6edfc34e55a3c8c556f8f94b29
msgid ""
"Do **not** use comments to disable code fragments. In production code "
"there should really be no commented or disabled code fragments. If you "
"really, really have a good reason to retain some fragment of unused code,"
" use #if or #ifdef to disable it, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:142 b78c11d218534389ace7b43992342b20
msgid "… and preferably use some descriptive macro instead of just ``0``, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:151 2fe59e5b0fee4d138a5bbd92ed63a392
msgid "Not sure how to do similar thing in Python… Anyone?"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:155 08062c5a1e43468182d765f92cf40d47
msgid ""
"But generally, there is little excuse to keep old, unused code fragments "
"in the code. One should really use the functionality provided by the "
"source code management system, such as git, instead. E.g. create a "
"special branch for storing the old, unused code – this way you will "
"always be able to merge this code into upstream in the future."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:157 1cd846b5b2d8407f88db1b6eb4230afe
msgid ""
"Do not hardcode values in the code! The only three numbers that are an "
"exception here and for which it is acceptable to hardcode them are: "
"``0``, ``1`` and ``-1``, and frankly the last two are still "
"controversial…"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:162 ed740758e54a4a319e6416c0d73dac44
msgid "Source Code management (Git) guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:165 d31560a5fa744c42b18deadd56751bc5
msgid "Use git to maintain all code for Qubes project."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:167 d3d094c518724ef19523a71b0ec55c5f
msgid ""
"Before you start using git, make sure you understand that git is a "
"decentralized Source Code Management system, and that it doesn’t behave "
"like traditional, centralized source code management systems, such as "
"SVN. Here’s a good `introductory book on git <https://git-"
"scm.com/book>`__. Read it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:169 9f94dd6c2af94c1a95b52ae0672b3c35
msgid ""
"Qubes code is divided into many git repositories. There are several "
"reasons for that:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:171 5b8551c1d6214fc4a0702a59d5d20f1c
msgid ""
"This creates natural boundaries between different code blocks, enforcing "
"proper interfaces, and easing independent development to be conducted on "
"various code parts at the same time, without the fear of running into "
"conflicts."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:173 f03804608fa44bafb7c9e85a4525b1fc
msgid ""
"By maintaining relatively small git repositories, it is easy for new "
"developers to understand the code and contribute new patches, without the"
" need to understand all the other code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:175 dcef8ff548194cd0afd9147d2d808682
msgid ""
"Code repositories represent also licensing boundaries. So, e.g. because "
"``core-agent-linux`` and ``core-agent-windows`` are maintained in two "
"different repositories, it is possible to have the latter under a "
"proprietary, non-GPL license, while keeping the former fully open source."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:177 5299b30f90fd4887a9afe17aebb94f22
msgid ""
"We have drastically changed the layout and naming of the code "
"repositories shortly after Qubes OS R2 Beta 2 release. For details on the"
" current code layout, please read `this article "
"<https://blog.invisiblethings.org/2013/03/21/introducing-qubes-odyssey-"
"framework.html>`__."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:184 b4a06876b19e4a179dcac1e55870ac6f
msgid "Commit message guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:187 92766490c21c4db0b4688dec68c2d17b
msgid ""
"Please attempt to follow these conventions when writing your Git commit "
"messages:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:189 eb31c8eb2e2b44a39aab802b458b2867
msgid "Separate the subject line from the body with a blank line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:191 0383876ef46846d2b62f576aa19ef57b
msgid "Limit the subject line to approximately 50 characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:193 82f5309ff1c44ba98b4362beb70f02bb
msgid "Capitalize the subject line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:195 68ce5ad8cb3d40dda1639c13b7d3bf29
msgid "Do not end the subject line with a period."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:197 f40b466325eb4b4eab9451d29a9c39a5
msgid "Use the imperative mood in the subject line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:199 03b21f0715e743388538412c0fdaf8ee
msgid "Wrap the body at 72 characters."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:201 6e53fe83722d484d937b22826772c743
msgid "Use the body to explain *what* and *why* rather than *how*."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:205 b25674e3da9b4f758d5dd5566d0b9951
msgid ""
"For details, examples, and the rationale behind each of these "
"conventions, please see `this blog post <https://chris.beams.io/posts"
"/git-commit/>`__, which is the source of this list."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:208 d371a2181a6b4a98a4c94ff68e150c0c
msgid "Security coding guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:211 28819eb2a98b4d7cbee19cf5db1bd514
msgid "As a general rule: **untrusted input** is our #1 enemy!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:213 47e20a0d1f924acb9f131647a1b1cabd
msgid ""
"Any input that comes from untrusted, or less trusted, or just "
"differently-trusted, entity should always be considered as malicious and "
"should always be sanitized and verified. So, if your software runs in "
"Dom0 and processes some input from any of the VMs, this input should be "
"considered to be malicious. Even if your software runs in a VM, and "
"processes input from some other VM, you should also assume that the input"
" is malicious and verify it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:215 21fcd591650d4d588eab55a6838cf4ce
msgid ""
"Use ``untrusted_`` prefix for all variables that hold values read from "
"untrusted party and which have not yet been verified to be decent, e.g.:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:230 c02b5e0a12a9418798f6cc9abc9cb8a9
msgid ""
"Use others variables, without the ``untrusted_`` prefix to hold the "
"sanitized values, as shown above."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:235 d3814b58ebe146ecb03fef99444df414
msgid "Python-specific guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:238 7fce35875dea441394df80a740aa8a56
msgid ""
"Please follow the guidelines `here "
"<https://peps.python.org/pep-0008/>`__, unless they were in conflict with"
" what is written on this page."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:243 0d719e6cf62c442d9b4c92f9034ad36a
msgid "C and C++ specific guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:246 1475ee5309634aeba2f0ec44184b3b0a
msgid "Do not place code in ``*.h`` files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:248 eec2c0e37d074d749dce461c618929af
msgid ""
"Use ``const`` whenever possible, e.g. in function arguments passed via "
"pointers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:250 0c09cbaf040b4731ad6f394284021fa0
msgid ""
"Do not mix procedural and objective code together – if you write in C++, "
"use classes and objects."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:252 eaa8d1c463f64a708a1d83f9158bb302
msgid ""
"Think about classes hierarchy, before starting to implement specific "
"methods."
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:257 67af20c7a4ad4441975da62f38e64187
msgid "Bash-specific guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../developer/code/coding-style.rst:260 c2f9d49ee8734a2cbf9d2e07b4dfc631
msgid ""
"Avoid writing scripts in bash whenever possible. Use python instead. "
"Bash-scripts are Unix-specific and will not work under Windows VMs, or in"
" Windows admin domain, or Windows gui domain."
msgstr ""

